ns to remove pathogens directly from the bloodstream?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spleen","Lymph nodes","Bronchus-associated lymphoid tissue","Gut-associated lymphoid tissue","Thymus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espleen\u003C/strong\u003E is uniquely designed to filter blood and remove pathogens directly from the circulation. It contains specialised sinusoids and macrophages that trap and destroy blood-borne microorganisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E filter lymph fluid rather than blood directly. They are positioned along lymphatic vessels and trap pathogens that enter through tissue spaces before they can reach the bloodstream.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchus-associated lymphoid tissue\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Egut-associated lymphoid tissue\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised areas of lymphoid tissue that provide local immune surveillance at mucosal surfaces. They do not directly filter blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethymus\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily responsible for T lymphocyte development and maturation. It does not have a significant role in directly filtering blood or removing pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The spleen filters blood directly through specialised sinusoids containing macrophages that trap and destroy pathogens","Lymph nodes filter lymphatic fluid rather than blood, trapping pathogens before they reach circulation","Mucosa-associated lymphoid tissues and thymus do not have direct blood filtering functions"],"references":["Esensten JH, Helou YA, Chopra G, Weiss A, Bluestone JA. CD28 Costimulation: From Mechanism to Therapy. Immunity. 2016 May 17;44(5):973-88. doi: 10.1016/j.immuni.2016.04.020. PMID: 27192564; PMCID: PMC4932896","Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, 